			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Advantages?<a name="55156"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 4 04 4:19 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Snow cougars in Iceclad are good AE targets.  Soulbinder in the zone, I always did it over by the tower of frozen shadow.  Lots of them there, just need to watch the shadow guardians.  When I quaded there with my druid and would get a guardian I'd just run to one side of the island, root it, and then take the kite to the other side of the island, but when AEing as a bard it isn't so easy.  You won't usually agro one while AEing, but if you get one while pulling then it may be simpler just to abort the attempt buy running really fast away and camping or hoofing it all the way to eastern waste.
<br />

<br />
You can also do a kind of crippled swarm kite at this level.  the 27 charm is mana free, but you don't have a reliable way to &quot;chant&quot; down your ex pet.  When I was trying it I'd just charm a new pet, and let it beat on my old pet but you have to do it on the run because the old pet won't stop and fight the new pet, it will keep after you.  I'd charm the new pet, toggle 2 targets back to old pet, /pet attack then agrokite the mess around.  It feels a little sloppy but if you get good at doing it that way then conventional swarming will be a peice of cake.
<br />

<br />
What I did for those levels?  Sounds cliche but get in a group and learn to twist while fighting and pulling, keeping the right songs up at the right phases of the battle can let you be more then just a 3 song junky.  Learn the art of having haste land right as you get back to the party with the pull, and not recasting it near the end of mob life in favor of getting manasong and regen pulsed so you can be off single pulling the next mob.  That is the kind of stuff that will get you noticed as a great bard.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">- I used to drive the short bus for a living.  Growing up on the internet leaves me uniquely qualified to handle retards at high speeds.</span></td>
